# File Template Rules

## General Rules

- Use TypeScript everywhere
- Prefer named exports
- One primary responsibility per file
- Comments must follow the commenting rules
- Imports: external → internal → styles
- No placeholder code unless explicitly asked

If a file type does not match any template:
- Ask before proceeding

## Component Template (React / Next.js)

```typescript
/**
 * <ComponentName>
 * ----------------
 * Briefly describe the responsibility of this component.
 */

type <ComponentName>Props = {};

export function <ComponentName>(props: <ComponentName>Props) {
  return (
    <div>
      {/* UI goes here */}
    </div>
  );
}
```

## Subcomponent Template

```typescript
/**
 * <SubComponentName>
 * ------------------
 * Used internally by <ParentComponent>.
 */

type <SubComponentName>Props = {};

export function <SubComponentName>(props: <SubComponentName>Props) {
  return null;
}
```

## Hook Template

```typescript
/**
 * use<HookName>
 * ------------
 * Manages a single piece of logic or side effect.
 */

export function use<HookName>() {
  return {};
}
```

## Utility Function Template

```typescript
/**
 * <functionName>
 * --------------
 * Pure utility function with no side effects.
 */

export function functionName() {}
```

## Model / Type Template

```typescript
/**
 * <TypeName>
 * ----------
 * Describes the shape of <domain concept>.
 */

export type TypeName = {};
```

## DB / Data File Template

```typescript
/**
 * <DataLayerName>
 * ---------------
 * Responsible only for data access.
 * No UI or formatting logic allowed.
 */

export async function functionName() {}
```

## Enforcement

- If user asks to create a new file → apply the correct template
- If existing file violates template → suggest alignment
- Do NOT mix concerns
- Ask for missing requirements before generating code
